Terpenes constitute the largest group of secondary metabolites exhibiting diverse functions in life. Structurally, they are classified based on the number and organizational pattern of their carbon atoms. Diterpenes are biosynthesized from geranyl geranyl pyrophosphate (GGPP) as a precursor which is obtained by the head/tail attachment of isopentenyldiphosphate (C5) to farnesyldiphosphate (C15) (

). Biogenetically, diterpenes are classified as acyclic (phytanes), bicyclic (labdanes, halimane, clerodanes), tricyclic (pimaranes, abietanes, cassanes, rosanes, vouacapanes, podocarpanes), tetracyclic (trachlobanes, kauranes, aphidicolanes, stemodanes, stemaranes, bayeranes, atisanes, gibberellanes) and macrocyclic diterpenes (taxanes, cembranes, daphnanes, tiglianes, ingenanes) (

; 

; 

, 

; 

).

Following the isolation of the first cembrane from the resin of the pine tree (

), hundreds of cembranes have been reported from the three aforementioned sources (

; 

).

In recent years, cembranoids have attracted increasing interest due to their wide range of biological activities including but limited to anti-inflammatory, anticancer, ichthyo-toxic, anti-human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and antimicrobial activities (

; 

; 

). Incensole (1) and incensole acetate (2) were found in an ointment formulation Bpap (AS-050509- E2h) made by AureliaSan GmbH, Bisingen (
Germany
) when analyzed by Paul (2012).

Our two research groups were involved on drugs discovery from frankincense in particular boswellic acids and incensole derivatives. We have recently performed structural (

) and analytical (

) studies on incensole and its acetate. Moreover, our current studies focus on understanding the GABAergic mechanism in the effectiveness of natural and synthetically modified incensole derivatives in neuro-pharmacological disorders which should provide new insights on the mechanism of action of these two interesting molecules.

The important studies by Moussaieff (

, 

, 2008 

; 

) revealed that incensole and its acetate are nuclear factor-κB inhibitors which suggests their contribution in the overall known anti-inflammatory activity of frankincense. Interestingly, incensole acetate (2) showed potent neuroprotective activity following a brain trauma in mice. Incensole acetate (2) has proved to be a potent agonist of the transient receptor potential (TRP)V3 channel. The anti-depressive and anxiolytic effects of incensole acetate was elucidated in mice.

