It is noteworthy mentioning that the method of extraction and to a lesser extent the quantification method has an influence on the final content of incensole and its acetate. This variation also holds correct with the same extraction method where distillation time, temperature and pressure can be critical factors. For example, quantification of incensole and incensole acetate in 

Boswellia sacra

(syn 

B. carteri

) (entries 1–3, 
Table 2
) showed that using hydrodistillation, no incensole was detected whereas employing extraction, 0.42% was observed. Interestingly, when the same extraction method was used while utilizing NIR instead of HPLC as a quantification method, a small variation is seen in the concentration of the incensole. When discussing these variations, it is vitally important to refer to the same sample for all analysis, otherwise, the comparison will be meaningless as other factors may contribute to the overall concentration e.g. environmental conditions and time of harvest of the resin (

,b). Another example supporting the above argument is the difference in concentration of both incensole and incensole acetate using two methods of extraction and different parameters within the same method (entries 12–15, 
Table 2
) as discussed above.

The biosynthesis of diterpenes starts from geranylgeranyl diphosphate (GGPP) ( A ). For the formation of incensole (1) and its acetate (2), Scheme 1 shows a possible biogenetic putative pathway. These two molecules are formed by loss of the pyrophosphate group from geranylgeranylpyrophosphate (GGPP) ( A ) to generate an active carbenium ion intermediate (B) which then undergoes a 1,14-cyclisation to generate the 14-membered carbenium ion scaffold (C). This may then either form cembrene A (D) via loss of a primary H + from the isopropyl group or cembrene C (E) via the loss of a tertiary H + from C-1 followed by an endocyclic conjugation (Paul, 2012;
). Cembrene A (D) and cembrene C (F) are likely to be the biosynthetic precursors of iso-serratol (E) and serratol (G), respectively, via a biosynthetic hydrolysis of the precursors.
reported serratol (G) as a biosynthetic precursor of incensole (1) and its acetate (2). An epoxidation of serratol (G) to afford epoxide (H) followed by an intramolecular cyclisation to form incensole (1) and then acetylation to incensole acetate (2) are likely the last steps of this reaction cascade ( Scheme 1 ).

Epoxide (7) was obtained treating 1 with m CPBA, which was then converted into acetate (8). On the other hand, epoxidation of incensole acetate (2) with m CPBA yielded a separable mixture of two regio-isomeric epoxides (8 and 9) each with 29% yield. The chemo-selectivity of the epoxidation of incensole (1) or its acetate (2) is not clear but might be attributed to the differences in the conformations of the two molecules due to complexation with the epoxidizing agent. Oxidation of the C-5 OH group with PCC provided incensone (10). Reduction of the C-5 ketone group of 10 with LiAlH 4 afforded a separable mixture of epi - incensole (11; 53%) and incensole (1; 28%) (
). Moreover, reduction of ketone 10 with NaBH
4 in
EtOH provided a 50:50 mixture of compounds 1 and 11 (
).

The activity profile of incensole acetate (2), has been evaluated by behavioral, pharmacological, and physiological assays. Moussaieff et al. have evaluated the psychoactive properties of incensole acetate (2) by activating TRPV3 channels in the brain (

). TRPV3 (Transient receptor potential vanilloid) is an ion channel associated in the perception of warmth in the skin (

; 

). The role of TRPV3 channels is unknown yet but TRPV3 mRNA has also been found in neurons all over the brain (

; 

).

Further experiments (
) proved a significant submissive behavior and potent antidepressant-like activity following the administration of incensole acetate (2) in much lower doses ( 10 mg / kg). Moreover, introduction of 1 or 5 mg /kg/day of incensole acetate (2) for three weeks resulted in a decrease in submissiveness of mice which provided additional proof the potent antidepressant effects of incensole acetate (2). This group has also reported a significant decrease of corticosterone levels which further supported the antidepressant effects (
).

The incensole acetate (2) was found to be the only selective TRPV3 agonist so far, therefore to explore the chemical space around incensole acetate (2), Pollastro et al., (2016) have synthesized 12 different derivatives of 2 and developed a complete structure activity relationship for TRPV3 (

). Incensole (1) and serratol (G) in addition to a series of semisynthetic derivatives of incensole were screened for transient receptor potential vanilloid 3 (TRPV3); the putative molecular targets agree with the observed psychotropic effect of incensole acetate (2) (

).


Boswellia

resins possess strong anti-inflammatory activities (

; 

; 

). 

described a bioassay-guided fractionation of 

Boswellia

resin and evaluated its anti-inflammatory effect using an inhibitor of the nuclear factor-kBα (I κBα) degradation in tumor necrosis factor (TNF) α- stimulated HeLa cells (

). Their study led to the isolation of two novel nuclear factor-κB (NF-κB) inhibitors from the resin, their structures were elucidated as incensole (1) and incensole acetate (2). Incensole acetate (2) inhibited the activation loop phosphorylation of TAK/TAB-mediated IκB kinase (IKK). This resulted in inhibiting cytokine and lipopolysaccharide-mediated NF-κB activation. However, incensole acetate (2) showed no effect on IKK activity 
in vitro
, and no suppression of IκB phosphorylation in co-stimulated T-cells. This suggests that the kinase inhibition is neither direct nor does it affect all NF-κB activation pathways. Interestingly, incensole acetate 2 is specific and did not interfere with TNF-induced activation of c-Jun N-terminal kinase (JNK) and p38 mitogen-activated protein kinase. (

).

Incensole acetate (2) also inhibited the production of inflammatory mediators in 
in vitro
model of C6 glioma and human peripheral monocytes (

). The effect of incensole acetate (2) was examined on the inflammatory process and on the recovery of neurobehavioral and cognitive functions in a mouse model of closed head injury (CHI). In the brains of post-CHI mice (

; 

; 

, 

), incensole acetate (2) reduced glial activation, inhibited the expression of interleukin-1β, and TNFα mRNAs, and induced cell death in macrophages at traumatized areas. Moreover, a mild hypothermic effect was also observed. Subsequently, incensole acetate (2) inhibited hippocampal neurodegeneration and exerted a beneficial effect on the functional outcome after CHI. This was observed by reduced neurological severity scores and improved cognitive ability in an object recognition test. This study attributed the anti-inflammatory activity of 

Boswellia

resin to incensole acetate (2) and related cembranoids. (

).

Incensole acetate (2) displayed a remarkable neuroprotective activity in an in vivo model, but its in vitro anti-inflammatory activity was smaller (IC 50 value more than 100 μM against NF-κB activation) (
). In order to evaluate the anti-inflammatory activity of modified incensole, Pollastro et al. synthesized 12 different derivatives of incensole acetate (2) and developed a complete structure activity relationship for NF-κB (STAT3) inhibition (
). Most of these derivatives with exception of 3 and 5 showed only weak activities with IC 50 values larger than 50, suggesting doubtful involvement of NF-κB in in vivo . Incensole (1), but not incensole acetate (2), proved potent on IL-6-induced STAT3 activation (IC 50 = 15.8 ± 2.88 μM) due to the involvement of STAT 3 in neuroinflammation. This suggests its involvements, secondary to enzymatic deacetylation, in the in vivo neuroprotective activity of incensole acetate (2).

The nonanoate (3) and the phenylacetate ester (5) derivatives of incensole (1) showed a potent inhibitory activity on NF-κB activation with IC 
50
values of 35.5 ± 1.1 and 22.4 ± 2.4 μM, respectively. Furthermore, incensole nonanoate (3) (
Scheme 3
) also inhibited STAT3 (IC 
50
= 38.7 ± 3.99 μM), while all the other analogs were inactive. Interestingly these inhibitors (incensole derivatives) of NF-κB are devoid from other NF-κB inhibitors as they lack electrophilicity and redox properties (

). Pollastro and coworkers (

) suggested that incensole derivatives are good for the inhibition of transcriptions factors (NF-κB and STAT3) as both are involved in inflammation. For example, incensole (1) and its nonanoate ester (3) could inhibit the activity of both NF-κB and STAT3 (

).
